The Republican Party's Strategy Against Obama's Reelection
Republican leaders have justified their policy with the necessity of fighting electoral fraud.
The Brennan Center, however, describes such fraud as a myth with the fact that electoral fraud is less common in the U.S. than the number of people who die after a lightning strike.
Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the U.S. over the past decade.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on election participation.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, in the United States, federal elections are held by states.
And in this spirit, most U.S. governments have been promulgating new laws since 2009 that make the process of election or listing difficult.
This phenomenon grew after the November 2010 election, during which 675 new Republican deputies in 26 states were added.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the right to vote were submitted in 41 states in 2011.
New electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws restrict the period for elections in advance, invalidate the right to register on the voter list on the day of the elections, and deprive citizens of the right to vote in the criminal register.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID card.
The first state to introduce this requirement was Indiana.
The Indian Act was ratified by the Supreme Court of the United States in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this procedure to other states.
Over the past two years, 34 states have supported proposals for such laws to force voters to submit photo ID cards.
It should be noted that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million people of voting age, do not possess a photo ID issued by their state government agency.
Moreover, about five million new voters did not have such a passport in 2012.
Purchasing the required ID card in addition often costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions unreasonably affect young people, members of minorities and people with low incomes.
25% of African Americans, 15% of people with incomes below $35,000; 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 therefore do not have the required photo ID.
And that is not all.
Students who are known as voters for their inclination toward democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID card issued by their school in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of hunting or fishing clubs who choose rather Republican candidates to use cards issued by those clubs in the election.
Until 2004, no country required a citizenship certificate for elections.
The first such request was made by Arizona.
Since 2011, about twelve states have passed laws that require voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the number of votes from the Hispanic minority.
It should be noted that two out of three Hispanics prefer the Democratic Party.
Republican lawmakers in 2011 endorsed laws in eight states that disregard voter registration on election day.
In addition, they restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters who wish to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns helped register about 10 million people.
Measures taken after 2009, however, caused a decrease in the registration of new voters in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
Republican lawmakers then passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the period for early elections.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, Afro-Americans made up 33% of voters who voted in advance, despite only 13% of African-American voters in that state.
It was the same with the Spaniards.
They made up only 11% of all voters, but 24% of the citizens voting in advance.
On the other hand, whites, who represented 76% of all voters, made up only 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic lawmakers and their supporters were very strongly opposed to passing laws that restrict voter registration.
Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
In order to suspend the most controversial laws, the U.S. Attorney General even intervened.
The damage was partially reduced.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring a photo ID card.
However, the new rules will undoubtedly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics speak primarily of the bias of the passed laws and see them as an obvious attempt to influence the results of the 2012 elections in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states where these laws were passed accounted for 171 of the 270 votes in the electorate needed to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is already certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on election participation.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Detection of prostate cancer: to undergo examination or not?
The PSA test yielded sometimes false results, which were false negative or even false positive, leading to unnecessary medical interventions.
All this even increased the hesitation of men who were already so reluctant to go to the examination at all.
To be examined or not?
We asked for the opinion of two experts.
Studies conducted in the U.S. have shown high levels of contamination among individual test groups, so it is difficult to interpret these results and make valuable recommendations.
Another study, this time European, found a difference in mortality between patients who underwent the examination and those who did not.
This study also showed after a 12-year interval that those who did not go to the examination had a 30-40% higher risk of developing metastases.
So I recommend testing from age 50 or from age 40 if your immediate relative had prostate cancer.
Men of African American descent are also more at risk.
The key is to make the right decision once the cancer is detected.
There are aggressive types of cancer and those that are indifferent.
Therefore, it is necessary to correctly explain to the patient the degree of danger of his type of cancer, offer him possible alternatives, not necessarily treat prostate cancer, which has no long-term impact on life, and focus in these cases on active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer are not treated because their type of cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
Instead, we will offer them active surveillance and offer treatment in case of disease progression.
More and more accurately we set criteria to help you decide which type to treat and which not.
However, I recommend taking the examination.
It is important to have an interview with a doctor and determine whether it is appropriate to undergo the examination or not.
