Higgs boson explored
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a justified uproar last summer.
There is an opinion that this boson is involved in the mechanism that is responsible for all matter in the universe.
And then it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model – our best or “least bad” explanation of the nature and behavior of matter – which, however, has not yet been empirically observed.
However, physicists are still not 100% sure that this is the Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have an entirely new particle available, which is very similar to the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
New data released this week during the major physics congress in Kyoto rather confirms this, but we still lack all the data to be absolutely sure.
However, let’s assume that this is the Higgs boson, as the risk of error seems small, and let’s look at what it is.
In this world, there is a completely undeniable law, according to which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule cannot be bypassed – and don’t try to do it too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a similar law: Pauli’s exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same “quantum state” – this “state” roughly creates some of their properties.
He also divides particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, who obediently follow the Pauli principle.
And at the other end are the bosons, the anarchists who do not value anything at all – not this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the device (by the way absolutely amazing), which is The Particle Adventure, in the Berkeley laboratories: the mesons, which we will leave unnoticed here, and the "force particles", by which great natural forces are spread and with which the Higgs boson is probably somehow associated.
However, it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as one might think.
If you read this article, it’s because of a boson with an unusual banality: a photon, or a “light particle”, which is the “bearer” of an electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes its direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field in this particular place, similar to a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this “interference” an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) arises, and this wave is nothing but a photon – and therefore one of the bosons, the “bearers of force.”
A more stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, with the only difference that it is necessary to "disturb" another field, the Higgs field, in order for this boson to appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; very high energy values must be achieved to excite it, similar to the freezing level of a pond, where only a very large balloon is shrinking.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge accelerator of the part as the accelerator in the CERN laboratory – a large hadron accelerator with a circle of 27 km! – in order to produce such energy.
An analogy with the electromagnetic field is once again useful for us to clarify the relationship between Higgs and matter.
Not all particles or materials react with electromagnetic fields.
Some, such as magnets, do so, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold on its own on the refrigerator.
And it’s also true that not all particles react with the Higgs field: those that do so have a certain mass, while others (like a photon, let’s look at it) don’t have it.
And Ms. Nováková asks why all these researches are what “we’ll bring”?
From a scientific point of view, it is a confirmation of the validity of the standard model (SM), which allows physicists to investigate any discrepancy between the observations and the predictions of SM.
Not a few physicists literally wish to find them, because the slightest difference could open up space for “new physics” and close up some gaps in the model.
It is necessary to state that the model has so far huge shortcomings, it does not bring any explanation of gravity (angle!) or dark matter, which makes up approximately 80% of the cosmic matter (angle!).
However, CERN has not yet discovered such contradictions.
Reactions
The responses of these researches in the everyday life of Mr. and Mrs. Novakov can only be predicted very hard, but it would be a mistake to believe that there will be no one.
At the very beginning of the 1960s, the laser pioneers in Bell’s laboratories had no idea of the revolution their work would bring about.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing more.
Physicist Willard Boyle – who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who created the first constant laser beam (the previous beams were pulsating) in 1962, I have already said – the laser was initially considered such a “labor toy”.
Just imagine it...
In addition, the application can also result from all the instruments surrounding the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work focused on optics.
This sensor, although Boyle did not initially plan it at all, now serves as the “eye” of all digital cameras in the world and won him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that activities around the LHC must necessarily change our lives, but it means that one really never knows...
Palliative Care – The Best Way to Get Away from Life
Through its Commission for Dignely Dying, Quebec has recently engaged in the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate is expected to continue in the near future and the draft law is also being prepared.
There is still a lot of work to be done in this important area.
The Le Devoir magazine tried to look at this issue in more detail.
Less than a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that fed him gave him a two-year delay.
“They gave me five years of life and it’s already seven,” he says without emotion on his bed at the Victor-Gadbois Palliative Care House in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
“It’s still a shock, you can’t prepare for this,” he adds.
The sickness has done its job: an enormous weakness makes it impossible for him to take himself to the toilet or just eat himself.
Resignedly, he looks at a tasty-looking breakfast and agrees to help him eat.
He is bold and even smiles, speaks to strangers who stop at him, brings him medicines, offers a bath.
The courage to die.
“My greatest desire is to get rid of that diarrhea, it humiliates me,” he confesses.
A few hours later, a team of doctors found a cure for his problem.
"A lifetime one learns that men urinate standing," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois facility.
Returning to the childhood stage is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the abilities of that person" whether he accepts that return, the psychologist says.
In the opinion of a number of people involved in palliative care, crucial moments take place at the very heart of such a return.
Patients who enter the home with palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
Their prognosis is up to three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses who take care of them does not provide them with so-called "medical" care.
In the case of Mrs. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "of suffocation at full consciousness".
But my illness allowed me to discover my children.
“I have good kids,” he adds.
“I don’t have any wishes in my life anymore,” she says, and then she agrees that we put a breathing apparatus on her.
However, he is still looking forward to his son’s last visit from Italy in the coming days.
The Victor-Gadbois home, in collaboration with a group of volunteers, provides nutritional care for the body.
This is how palliative care appears when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed per 11,700 inhabitants.
This is very little if we realize that we will all die someday.
Here life continues in optimal conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors in the home.
Whether it’s a level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When a person dies, you can give him, for example, a bunch of brandy or pepsi, according to taste.
Diabetics no longer need to monitor their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night they brought a beer to Mr. X, who later in the night died.
This morning, his son drank a beer in honor of his deceased father.
"We help patients as well as their loved ones," says Nathalie Savard, director of care services.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, the days go one by one, but they don’t resemble each other.
Alongside a ninety-three-year-old man who rejoices at the last meeting with his family thoroughly underpinned on his pillows while drinking him in his honour, a tragic thirty-six-year-old man dies surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children after trying out all options to survive.
"For half a year, there are always three to five beds, which are intended for people with cancer under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who come to the Victor-Gadbois home come here from their homes, 47% from hospitals.
Access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care that is designed to alleviate suffering once the sick person reaches the final stage of their life, whether it is at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Home and the Society for Home Palliative Treatment of the Grand Montréal Area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care provided to cancer patients.
And it is this fundamental lack of access to health care in Quebec that leads to the fact that a number of doctors specializing in palliative care are concerned about the adoption of the euthanasia and assisted suicide law.
Since October, a manifesto has been signed in circulation by leaders in palliative treatment such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, in which they demonstrate their disapproval of such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec healthcare system is not efficient enough to ensure access to high-quality palliative care before it can be agreed to euthanasia.
As she says, she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days at the emergency in tremendous pain without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
They fear that patients will not ask for killing because they are not receiving proper care.
At the same time, a number of oncologists take care of their patients until the last moment, regardless of the adverse prognosis.
Hélène Richard’s chances of survival were already minimal when she abandoned the demanding chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I stopped treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she told us.
And she told me it was over!
There is no omnipotent care.
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their doctors for not fulfilling their wishes when the palliative pique team relieved their pain.
However, palliative care is not all-powerful in treating pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Society for Home Palliative Care in the Grand Montréal area, patients are prevented from treating pain in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use palliative sedatives that sleep the patient until the moment of death, either shock or let sedatives be given permanently.
We cannot pretend that we do not perceive this part of suffering.
Patients who do not get rid of pain will have more and more access to palliative sedatives.
Patients who are not given a sedative always say the same thing: “I want to die.”
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to grant me euthanasia” but rather “I want you to relieve me of my pain.”
