In the case of Bitcoin, all the nodes of the network are current account book depositaries, controllers, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
This way, the network can verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in a public book of current accounts, which is distributed across the network.
The key phase is the recording of this new transaction in this book.
It takes place by solving a mathematical task assigned to computers, whose solver, a kind of temporary central banker, will have the right to write this additional line.
This is the phase of cutting a file; i.e. the transformation of a huge file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, and only then "cut off" the whole.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific footprint (nearly zero at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes will easily check its correctness.
The transaction will then appear indestructibly connected to the chain of all other transactions; any adjustment would change the footprint.
If a user would want to pay twice with the same money very quickly in a row (within ten minutes) for the purpose of fraud, the network will only confirm one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned because each of them has a different footprint.
The computer that solves the challenge will win 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this remuneration is regularly divided into two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to one hundred million, so there is room for margin.
The difficulty of the assigned task also increases with the increasing level of calculation.
The network has experienced its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been hacked and stored bitcoins stolen.
“The scale used is not related to the protocol itself,” says Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also checks the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
This also applies to cash.
Major players like Wikipedia reject gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed the book of current accounts and proved that almost 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, huge discounts were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul engaged in converting bitcoin into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of the educational book on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payment, but it uses the Bitcoin system to authenticate transactions, which are cheaper.
In addition, the user manages his/her identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system is easily set up with traders where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
Just give an address that can be “photographed and recognized” by the phone, Pierre Noizat says, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems and transition to more horizontal systems.
“Bitcoin will take a while before it gets established, but 2013 could be crucial,” he predicts.
In addition, the ECB in its report anticipates a re-evaluation of various risks, which are now considered to be increased if this type of money is successful.
