Difficult Work on Egyptian Constitution
President Mohamed Morsi is playing poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history due to the proclamation of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, he decided to play vabank.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of the opinion of all others, that the Constituent Assembly will approve the final text tomorrow.
Less than a week ago, the head of state gave this assembly another two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has used the provisional text, which has been repeatedly amended, undermining the country’s constitutional stability and leading to legal disputes.
This new initiative has only further strengthened the fragmentation of the country.
From the opposition’s point of view, the president persists in his “autocratic delusion”, continues to “violate his word” and “trap the law”.
His supporters, however, assure that this is a means to tackle the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to accelerate the transition process.
There should be a referendum in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention of clarifying the text to the Egyptians article by article.
For the president, it is also a way to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while protests are stirring up across the country.
As confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Mohamed Morsi appears to be convinced that Egyptians will vote for.
Especially because this hastily organized vote puts the Egyptian people before an ultimatum: “Either you approve my text, or I will retain unlimited powers,” which would otherwise end after the approval of the new constitution.
And in this particular atmosphere yesterday, 85 deputies of the aforementioned constituent assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
The majority of liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, shortly before the proclamation of the constitution, they knocked their doors with no opportunity to make their views public.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities have taken their steps.
In order to reach the resolution capacity, 11 people from the ranks of substitutes were rushed up yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising then that articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
The commentators also commented on the fact that one of the few disputes that day revolved around... the hour for prayer, when some members of the committee held the view that the hours in the meeting room were not properly arranged.
The text, which was voted last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, remains ultimately the same as the version of the 1971 Constitution, stating that “the principles of Sharia law are the primary source of law.”
The Salafist parties, for which the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental requirements, hoped to replace the term "principles" with the term "rules", allowing for stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for the rest of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” the liberals argue, who see it as a speech problem.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is carried out through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which entrusts the University of Al-Azhar with an advisory role, in particular in matters of checking compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because “the people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
This can be seen in the beginnings of theocracy.”
Liberals are even more concerned about the fact that the next university rector should be less moderate than the current one.
So far, no specific religious consequences have been shown.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a civilian state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text were not ulamians, but university staff, many of whom graduated from French schools," said Alexis Blouet, who is preparing work on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, he agrees that "there may be contradictions regarding the interpretation of Article 220, because the terms used in it belong to the religious dictionary.
In particular, there is a reference to “fiqh” [Islamic Legal Science].
And in the future, the question may arise to what extent civil judges are competent to comment on this."
The text approved yesterday is heavily criticized in addition to the religious pages due to the extended powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there have been significant restrictions against the former regime.
Another controversial place: powers entrusted to the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military officials, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by the parliament, but by the National Defense Council.
Furthermore, proceedings against civilians will not be prohibited in military courts, as the human rights association has demanded.
These associations speak of their doubts in connection with the text which they consider to be against freedom.
The crime of blasphemy isined and insult is still prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no article deals with the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture laid down in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak in a television address last night, protests are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will then demonstrate on Saturday.
