Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was accepted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on November 12, 2008).
Poland started a close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and has participated in a number of ESA projects over the years to come.
However, the trip to space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights before World War II; but they did not always encounter understanding.
I would like to recall, for example, A. Šternfeld’s lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on 6 December 1933 presented the ideas of his pioneering work The Entry into Cosmonautics.
The thoughts of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold and after years Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his entry into space in France.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 – 1966) became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and written a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of cosmonautics and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the other side of the moon was named after him.
In 1925 a railway was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is unclear whether the missile was to be used to start the drone or to brake it.
Information about this is only known from the press.
In 1933, the Polish artillery began to use missiles.
The research was carried out by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfk and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckieg.
From the conserved materials it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric fighter missile, designed by the engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the professional press, and in the following year the work Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza of the author Leliwy-Krzywoblocký was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) coordinated all the projects for the military use of missile technology.
The Committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity its activities ended with the beginning of the war.
Other works devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, the company is mentioned in the November edition of the 1954 issue of Problems magazine, which contains four more comprehensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, by Prof. M. Subotowicz, it is proposed to create a company that will be engaged in cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already underway and it was clear that space research was a prospective field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has sought to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and already in the autumn the PTA became a full member.
And in the following year, the first Chairman of the PTA Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became Vice-Chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has contributed significantly to the development of the very successful meteorological missile RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish missile to conduct scientific research.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket with a reach of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 missile were launched in the Bled Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another development type was already supposed to be capable of actual scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was supposed to have a range of up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the height of the wind.
However, in 1962 further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type missile was Meteor-1 developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
Meteor-1A had a space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum reach for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aeronautical Institute was developing the Meteor-2 rocket, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a launch weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a weight of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Subsequently, versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
In 1960, Poland joined the Committee for Space Research (COSPAR) and two years later, the National Committee for Space Research (COSPAR) was created.
Poland also participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites under the Interkosmos program, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remkov.
