Last Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane had mechanical problems and we had to wait for the next plane to arrive.
So we had a lot of time thinking about boredom.
I will not lie to you.
Waiting half a day at the airport for the next flight is pretty annoying, despite being distracted by books, magazines, and iPhones (not to mention duty-free stores).
But some scientists and experts on child development are increasingly coming up with the praise of boredom.
They say it’s good for us (and our kids) to get bored sometimes.
It forces the brain to go in interesting directions, which can encourage creativity.
And given that most of us are constantly connected to some screen these days, we have no chance of enjoying boredom.
Should we support boredom?
Yes is.
and no.
But I will return to that.
First, like many people, I assumed that boredom is a relatively new phenomenon that occurred with the advent of more free time.
But as Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the Canadian University of Calgary, who is the author of Boredom: A Lively History, says (Yale University Press, 2011).
“In fact, boredom has a long history,” he said.
On the walls of Pompeii was found a Latin inscription relating to boredom, dating from the first century AD.
And then there is also the question of how we define boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After looking at the research literature and presenting the idea to a target group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience "I wanted to do something that would satisfy me, but I was unable to do it."
Boredom differs from apathy by the fact that a person is not involved in anything, but would like to be.
He says that with apathy there is no urge to do anything.
He says that the core of boredom is "a disturbance in the process of attention, associated with a bad mood and a feeling of slowly passing time."
Depression can be a lot like depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while they may have a relationship with each other, boring people tend to see the problem as the environment or the world, while people who are depressed see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we feel bored when we only have trouble concentrating.
In their study “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,” which was published in September in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues pointed to a previous experiment in which participants listened to a tape on which the person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud and unrelated television program in the next room, others heard it so quietly that they barely noticed it, while the third group did not hear it at all.
Those who listened to the television program quietly more boredom than the other two groups – they had trouble concentrating but were not sure why and attributed these troubles to boredom.
When trying to concentrate on a difficult or engaging task, disturbance of attention can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when you’re doing something boring, “like looking for the wrong parts on the factory line, distracting music can help keep you from getting bored.”
