For four euros, carriers in the area of an Indonesian volcano gamble with their lives and health as they carry 70 kilos of sulfur down the steep stone paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and there are those who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anta Wijayi, one of the 400 miners who make a living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
For this reason, it must travel every day to the bottom of the crater, where sulfur gases escape from the inside of the Earth and, when in contact with the air, move into a solid state.
After cutting out large blocks of sulfur, which together weigh up to 70 kilograms, he carries them on his shoulders in two bamboo baskets along narrow stone paths.
To the top of the volcano, which reaches 2,386 meters, it’s only 250 meters away, but it takes over 40 minutes for exhausted carriers to climb to the turtle pace as they maintain balance and carefully weigh their steps so they don’t slip and fall into the abyss.
They know that any stumbling could cost them their lives, as it happened to a French tourist who fell from the rocks of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Miners in Kawah Ijen earn five cents for every kilogram of sulfur they extract
When they’re upstairs, they take their way around tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys in a circus, and tiredly carry heavy baskets to the weight that the mining company has placed slightly lower, at an altitude of 1850 meters.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been mining in the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilogram of sulfur.
He then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used for the manufacture of light bulbs, entertainment pyrotechnics, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
"Because we usually carry 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each trip," Anto, who usually takes three trips a day, explains to us.
One trip takes him three hours and at the end is destroyed, but he can earn 138,000 rupees (11,5 euros) a day.
Although this seems to be a negligible sum for such inhumane effort, it’s three times what he would earn on the field.
"The daily salary of miners here is very high. For example, 15,000 rupees (1,2 euros) per day is paid for collecting coffee, and the salary for fourteen days is two million rupees (167 euros)," explains the carrier, who previously worked on the tourist island of Bali as a murderer.
There was his salary of 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work wasn’t that hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason that is as convincing in Indonesia as sulfur: “I married a young girl from Bali who is Hindu, and I took her to Java to convert to Islam.”
Anto has asthma, breathing badly, still coughing and eyes irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto risks his life three times a day in the Kawah Ijen volcano, whose sulfur has already begun to collect its tax on it, despite his face being protected by a special mask and glasses.
