“I’ll be working for another two years because I want to open a business or study Spanish or French,” he promises more than a solid English language.
This sympathetic and intelligent fate-stricken young man could be a tour guide, waitress or hotel receptionist, and instead do the job of a carrier.
He shares a dirty wooden cottage with other carriers and wakes up every day at two o’clock in the morning, as sulfur does not stop blowing out at night and its characteristic yellow color changes to blue and glowing darkness.
Despite the surrounding darkness, Anto runs into the crater and illuminates his way with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought for his money.
