Although the company has high incomes, it has not mechanized sulphur mining for cost savings, nor does it provide carriers working on their own and with such effort, any equipment.
In fact, they don’t even get a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) of the photography surcharge, which, along with the 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) ticket, are collected by nature park guards from tourists who come to take pictures of the volcano and its human mules.
“This work is for cattle, not people,” says Madrusin, a 42-year-old carrier who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to raise up to 110 pounds and assures us that he will be able to work "as long as possible" because he needs money to educate his three sons between the ages of 18 and 10.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano was my whole life
