Unainik, who balances his basket on his back, at 53 years old can load only 50 kilograms.
Every day, he and his colleagues extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks then transport on a steep road between the hive to a warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
“I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life,” Unainik says, opening his mouth wide and missing a few teeth.
Of his five sons, the oldest, thirty years old, also makes money mining sulfur.
Time goes by, but the constant misery of one of the world’s toughest crafts persists from generation to generation – the crafts carried out by human mules in Kawah Iljen.
