South America Summit Ends and the Lima Declaration Has Not Been Published
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Peru ended today without the release of the Lima Declaration, which was announced and allegedly signed by seven presidents present.
Efe has repeatedly attempted to gain access to the document signed at the sixth UNASUR meeting of heads of state and government, but representatives from both the Foreign Ministry and the Presidential Office, who initially stipulated that the document would be published after the summit, said it would later be published on the website of the Peruvian government.
They also said the content was published by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala in several brief press releases.
Journalists had limited access to information during the summit.
During the meeting, a video from the presidential assembly without sound was broadcast in the press room with the message "confidential session, audio transmission prevented".
A small amount of information available to journalists was provided by the press spokesmen of some of the governments present at the meeting, but not to the Peruvian spokesmen.
The only document published during the meeting was a list of presidents, which provoked the resentment of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media outlets asking for more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidential office sent an e-mail to the media with a “final statement” from the summit, but it was only a statement by President Humala, not an official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of the South American and Arab Countries (América del Sur-Países Árabes, ASPA), and even on this occasion the initially promised Lima Declaration was not published, despite the press’s ardent demand.
On the official website of ASPA it can be found that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, Peruvian authorities sought to ensure broadcasting for all journalists, but completely prevented the flow of information.
The summit ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept the ruling of the Hague Court of Justice, which resolves the border dispute between the two countries.
Peru’s President, Ollanta Humala, and Chile’s President, Sebastián Piñera, met during a regional meeting and confirmed that they will respect the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which on Monday will hear the defence speech of both sides to address the dispute launched by Lima against Santiago.
“We will work out and execute the verdict that will resolve the dispute that we are dealing with at this international court today,” President Humala and his Chilean counterpart said.
"Chile has been, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful settlement of disputes, conventions and international courts," Piñera said in a statement.
The confirmation by the two presidents that they would submit to the International Court of Justice decision was released after Colombia adopted the Bogotá Pact this week, expressing its submission to the judgments of the international court that ruled on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, and Colombia considered that decision to be completely wrong.
The summit took place without the presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chávez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 after the resignation of then-President Fernando Luga and did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was instructed to open the morning speeches and close the summit in Lima shortly after noon.
The president read the final document, in which he informed that 16 agreements were adopted and activities were planned on 31 projects between South American countries, with investments of $17 billion.
In addition to the agreements reached, he mentioned that UNASUR member countries would take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which agreements of residence are being extended."
“We are supporting actions to improve cooperation in the fight against civil uncertainty and international organized crime, to improve access to medicines and cheap internet in all corners of South America, and to jointly and effectively address the risks of natural disasters.”
When Europe is in crisis, “economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not have a winning essence, but should serve to expand our productivity and show our peoples a better future,” Humala added.
"We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve the transport connections of different parts of South America, especially rural and border areas ... so that our countries are better connected and create new economic ties," the Peruvian president said in a read speech.
He noted that five of these projects concern Peru and its cross axis from the coast to Brazil, and two related to better connections with Ecuador, but did not provide further details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to bring her back to the Union of South American Nations," from which she is currently excluded.
Another issue highlighted by the summit was the need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful region that is integrated and has good neighbourly relations.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before he attended the regional meeting that he hoped to meet in Mexico on Saturday with his Nicaraguan counterpart Daniel Ortega to respectfully consider the International Court of Justice’s ruling on the maritime border dispute, which is being challenged by Bogotá.
"It is possible that I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow," Santos said.
"We will discuss all solutions, none are excluded, nor a deal with Nicaragua that would require negotiations with this country," he said.
“I hope I will be able to tell President Ortega to conduct the negotiations in the most civilized and reasonable manner possible,” Santos said.
Santos and Ortega are scheduled to meet in Mexico on Saturday to attend the inauguration of President Enrique Peña Nieta.
During the summit, EU defence ministers met preliminarily to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defence in the region.
UNASUR members are Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay, although the latter is currently excluded.
Peru is the interim chairman of the regional bloc.
