Fabrizi was 21 when his test results were confirmed: HIV positive.
“It was like a lightning hit me,” he tells, recalling a moment of truth that the doctor tried to “soften a little,” but apparently without success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take his illness on his hips and began to inform himself about it with such dedication that he had already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the most recent patients of the HIV Unit at the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), to which he came in 1994 after several battles with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something unimaginable in the early 1990s when there was a lot of doubt, few treatment options, and greater stigma.
At the time, even the director of the Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) clinic did not say goodbye to him, "because he had a cutting wound."
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, there are many people who do not know about their disease and come only when the virus has caused destruction of the body and strengthened the immune system, and then become victims of accidental infections.
31 years since AIDS appeared in the world, or at least since the first documented cases, "it means a great success that the life expectancy of a patient who starts treatment in a timely and appropriate manner is exactly the same as in healthy people," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Guadalajara Civil Hospital with the fact that this information was confirmed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectologist and HIV/AIDS specialist Andrade Villanueva explained that scientists have concluded that since 2008 AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the length of survival and full life depends on the degree of impairment of the immune system of the patients who are diagnosed with the disease, while those who do not use drugs are better at it: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years and people with 500 CD4 cells up to 50 years.
Simply put, this means that one who is diagnosed with HIV at the age of 25 can, according to these findings, "live without problems up to 75 years with treatment," the doctor explained in the interview.
To highlight this progress, it is worth reminding that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality has decreased significantly in recent years and in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (the yearbook of the United Nations Joint Programme on HIV/AIDS – UNAIDS), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics.
In the state of Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and by May of this year, 187.
Why do people continue to die from illnesses?
"I think the problem is not in access to treatment.
This is what happens in our hospital.
The problem is that patients come in a very advanced stage because they do not know the state of infection, i.e. in the late stage of the disease.”
He adds a convincing figure: “Nine out of ten patients come when an associated infection is already manifested.The only thing we need to do to more influence the overall mortality rate is to diagnose the disease earlier, and therefore it is necessary to offer large-scale tests to detect the disease to all people who apply for them.”
In his proposal, he agrees with specialists and officials from the State Council for AIDS Prevention in the state of Jalisco and directly with patients like Fabrizio, who came to be tested in a private laboratory just because his friend did it, and despite his low age, he had AIDS and also suffered from Kaposi’s sarcoma, a tumor disease that is one of the usual complications.
“Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they’re going to die and don’t want to know anything else.
“If I’m going to die, I’d rather go out three times a week,” they say, but that’s not my case.
I’ve been changing to the better, eating healthy, exercising, taking medication.”
His parents only know that he has cancer.
I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I lead an active sex life, but responsibly, I take care of myself and the other person,” says Fabrizio, who accepted the call to share his experience with the daily MILENIO JALISCO, to motivate today in the framework of the World AIDS Day with his testimony those who are afraid.
“Let them get tested.If they risk, let them know as soon as possible if they are HIV positive, it’s better.And if they’ve been diagnosed, let them realize that they can live like anyone else when they’re responsible.”
This message summarizes the motto of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
