The ruling approved by the U.S. Court of Appeal, which does not recognize Grupo Vitro’s debt restructuring established by the bankruptcy in Mexico, creates a bad precedent for any national enterprise with branches in a neighboring country and solvency problems.
So it seems that the restructuring procedures of companies that are permitted by Mexican laws do not apply in the country of strips and stars despite international agreements.
The endorsement of the judge Harlin Hal’s judgment of June 15 last year at the North Texas Bankruptcy Court left Mexican firms in practice defenseless against the possibility of confiscation of their assets on the other bank of the el Bravo River.
However, the ruling opens the door to the U.S. Supreme Court for the major Mexican glass manufacturer, appealing against three irregularities.
To begin with, while the judge in this case argues that the creditors are to be guided by the US insolvency law, the New Orleans-based Fifth District Court of Appeal says that the main procedure provides for bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
First, this would indicate a lack of knowledge of international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of multinational enterprises.
Basically, for this purpose, the United Nations Model Law for Unification of International Commercial Law was created, which arbitrates the organization of the American Law Institute.
Second, the judgment states that without the voting of the branches in the internal structure of the enterprise, where the debt of the parent company Vitro towards the branches is recognised, the majority required to approve the restructuring would not be achieved.
