Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Basketball world runner Héctor "Hetin" Reyes has been associated with this hall sport for more than 60 years and has traveled the world thanks to him.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as many memories of local basketball history as Héctor “Hetin” Reyes has.
Reyes had been involved in the sport for more than 60 years before he suffered a stroke on a wheelchair in 2008, whether as a younger player, a player of the BSN National Basketball League, owner and coach of the Vaqueros de Bayamón National Basketball League team, or president of the Puerto Rico Basketball Federation.
“I’ve played a lot of roles in basketball throughout my life, including several at the same time, like when I was the president of the BSN National League in the 1990s, the general manager of the national team and the president of the federation,” Reyes recalled while visiting reporters at his home in Bayamon, where he has lived for more than 50 years with his faithful wife, Isabel.
“Basketball was my life.”
Reyes is not exaggerating in his claim.
The walls of his house, which are almost all decorated with photographs and souvenir items from his long career, testify to this.
Bayamón in the Heart
With the greatest movement of all the guards are those that recall his performance in Los Vaqueros from the mid-1950s, where he was a player until 1982, when he also celebrated 15 years as a co-owner or owner of the team.
“That was my best years, the ones I the most, because I had the opportunity to participate with the Los Vaqueros since 1967 in eight championships, whether as a owner, co-owner, or coach.
It was a series of successful years, including five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one championship – in 1981, when Jerome Mincy made his BSN debut.
At that time, the team took over “Cuco” Ortiz, who was an outstanding leader,” Reyes said.
“I remember when Gene Bartow, who was a former coach at the University of Alabama in Birmingham, told me, ‘I have a two-meter-long player for you.
Do you want him?”
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gausse, who became a member of the team and one of our best shooters.
I remember he said that if Mincy brings Bayamon a championship victory, then Gausse will contribute to the next."
Gausse the championship for the Los Vaqueros team, but only at a distance, since he had already served as president of the basketball federation in 1988.
At that time, he wanted to fully devote himself to his functions and enjoy Mincy’s position in the national team.
“I remember the first time we defeated the United States at the qualifying Olympics in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the World Cup in 1990, where we finished quarter, but we should have had the bronze if not the Canadian referee who let us repeat the final pitch," Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you’ve ever seen?
He is among the best, as well as the one who defeated the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favourite was the national team at the Pan-American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and swept out the team of the United States, which was quite similar to the one that blown out the bronze at the World Cup.
