Actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, who was born on 21 September 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, was world famous for the lead role of John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the television series Dallas, in which he embodied a man who acted relentlessly and was conspicuous and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as J.R. Ewing in the Dallas TV series became a symbol of hunger in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new Dallas series, died on Friday afternoon from complications related to cancer, according to the family’s official announcement to the Associated Press by Dallas production company Warner Bros.
“Larry has returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he has played the iconic role he loved most,” his family said.
Larry's family and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for Thanksgiving.
"Linda Gray, who represented his wife in both the original and the new series, was with Hagman at the time he died in the Dallas hospital," her agent Jeffrey Lane said in a statement.
He brought joy to everyone he knew.
“He was creative, generous, funny, kind, kind and talented and I will miss him very much.
He was unique and lived his life to the fullest," Linda Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and he himself admitted to drinking a lot for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found on his liver and Hagman underwent a transplant.
Years before broadcasting Dallas, Hagman became famous on television as a decent guy in the lightweight comedy I Dream of Jeannie broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
Here he played the character of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive girl (the gin) played by Barbara Eden, and takes her home to live together.
He also starred in two comedies that were broadcast only briefly, namely The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His performances in films included roles that were well received by critics: The Group, Harry and Tonto, and Primary Colors.
But it was Hangman’s masterpiece in the form of the incredibly repugnant J.R. that brought him to the star-top.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other personalities around them was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional slogan “Who Shoot Jayara?”, which was meant to arouse expectations about the thrilling work, when Hangman’s character is almost murdered, has caused not only a huge array of speculation from viewers around the world, but also risking millions of dollars in rates.
This has also helped to a record in viewing.
The November 1980 episode, in which the answer was revealed, had an average of 41 million television viewers.Dallas became the second most watched entertainment show in history after the end of the MASH series in 1983, which had 50 million viewers.
J.R. was shot by his brother-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby).
Kristin and J.R. became pregnant and he then threatened to call her a prostitute if she did not leave the city.
Hagman played Ewing, an insatiable greedy man with a charismatic smile: a deceitful businessman and an unfaithful husband who tried to get his wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), who was an alcoholic, locked in a hospital.
"I know what I want J.R. to have on the tombstone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should be: “Here lies the honourable citizen J.R. Ewing.”
This is the only thing he failed.
Victoria Principal, who starred in the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as someone who was "great on the canvas and beyond."
He is unforgettable and irreplaceable to the millions of fans in the world and in the hearts of all of us who have been lucky to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new Dallas series were broadcast by TNT a few months ago with great success.
"Five episodes of the second series have already been filmed and the sixth is just being filmed," the TV station said.
Immediately after Hangman’s death, there was no statement from Warner or TNT about how the series would continue.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who shone in classical works such as the musicals South Pacific and Peter Pan.
Mary Martin was a very young girl when in 1931 she gave birth to Larry, whose father was her husband, lawyer Ben Hagman.
In the early 1950s, Larry tried his luck on the theater scenes in New York and then served in the British Air Force from 1952 to 1956.
There he met the young Swedish designer Maj Axelsson, with whom he married.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and for a long time they lived in the California city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he published his autobiographical book Hello Darlin: Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life.
“I didn’t put anything that I knew could hurt someone or hurt them in some way,” he told the press.
After a liver transplant, he started promoting organ donation and worked as a volunteer in a hospital where he helped fearful patients.
“I advise them, I give them courage, I meet with them when they go for surgery and after,” he said in 1996.
I try to give them comfort in the sense of “don’t worry, it will be a bit annoying for a while, but you’ll be healthy.”
He was also an anti-smoking activist and participated in various campaigns.
Starts a course exploring the "end of the world"
Every week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear warfare, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When religion professor Stuart Charmé decided that this semester would be a course on the end of the world, he knew it was an irresistible attraction: the end of the "long number" of the Maya calendar, which is due to come on December 21, has caught many people as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what was ahead of him in the next few months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, the budget gap that some call “the debt Armageddon,” and the growing conflict in which Israel is entangled, the place where, according to Christians theorizing the end of the world, the Apocalypse begins.
"I didn't realize this would be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey this week.
When one considers what is happening in the world today as if we had 30 days left, it’s really a good time.
And remember that bad means good for apocalyptic thinking.
And it’s not the only professor offering courses on the “end of the world” in this semester, which is theoretically the latest in history.
At Temple University, expert assistant Barry Vacker hosts a course on "Middles, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear warfare, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
“We’re uncovering why these ideas are expanding over time,” he says, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that govern certain human behaviors.
If, for example, nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, a war can break out.
This month, students analyze films on apocalyptic themes and explore how they differ from real-life examples.
“I tried to inform students about what is possible, likely, credible, and impossible,” says Vacker.
At the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, Latin American history professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of art history and anthropology, gathered together to organize a course called The End of the World.
“We’re not attaching ‘2012’ because we’re always counting on the possibility of arranging the course again in case the world doesn’t end,” Restall said.
Despite the “threatening ruin,” students have to study, create projects, and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will take place on the eve of the Apocalypse, giving students no choice but to work "until the evening of the expected end of the world," Restall said.
Courses have become very popular.
"It stretched out in two hours," Restall said of his course for high-average students enrolled by 35.
For weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, we received emails asking if there was still room.
Students themselves assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves,” said Bridgid Robinson, 23, a religion and sociology student at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey.
And so apocalyptic, secular or religious thinking is only a matter of comfort or its absence.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student of psychology and nursing, said he has seen all the apocalyptic movies.
“I’ve never heard of an hour before in which this could be taught,” he said.
“I enjoy it.”
But no confessed student, let alone a professor, has said that he believes in the end date of December 21.
“Our first project was about Maya predictions, and in a way we are refuting them,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old graduate student at Temple University in West Chester.
“The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it’s just a key point in the calendar,” Restall said.
But he added that in Western culture there is an apocalyptic anxiety dating back several centuries, by which people respond to changes in their surroundings by predicting the end of the world.
The rise of this speculation was caused by the Internet.
“People don’t think about it elsewhere,” he said.
This is the case mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at the University of La Salle, who is lecturing in the Philippines this year, responded quickly to the question of whether he knew of any course there on “the end of the world.”
“The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world,” he wrote, suggesting an exception to the Supreme Office.
We have grace from the Pope.
Restall noted that many days of the Last Judgment have been talked about over the years, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
The date is taken lightly by students and professors.
Several of them said they intended to go to the "end of the world" celebration.
"I'll probably call a few friends to laugh together," explained 20-year-old communication student Samira Ford.
